00:02:39.420 --> 00:02:41.730
Today we'll just talk a little
bit first about turtles just

00:02:41.730 --> 00:02:43.420
to get a sense of why--

00:02:43.420 --> 00:02:45.470
besides the fact that
they're cute, yes--

00:02:45.470 --> 00:02:48.350
but why we care and why we're
spending a lot of time and

00:02:48.350 --> 00:02:52.450
effort, and why it's worth your
guys' time besides the

00:02:52.450 --> 00:02:56.010
ancillary benefit of nice
weather and maybe a tan or a

00:02:56.010 --> 00:02:58.730
sunburn to think about them.

00:02:58.730 --> 00:03:01.300
So I'm just going to provide
an overview of the three

00:03:01.300 --> 00:03:04.590
turtle species we primarily see
at Glover's Reef, which is

00:03:04.590 --> 00:03:08.820
where the survey takes
place in Belize.

00:03:08.820 --> 00:03:12.030
The three turtles we'll talk
through are loggerhead turtle,

00:03:12.030 --> 00:03:14.460
green turtle, and hawksbill
turtle.

00:03:14.460 --> 00:03:16.930
So this is a photo of a
loggerhead turtle similar,

00:03:16.930 --> 00:03:18.560
actually, to Winnie's photo.

00:03:18.560 --> 00:03:20.882
This is in the New
York Aquarium.

00:03:20.882 --> 00:03:23.230
The photos often for loggerheads
are very popular

00:03:23.230 --> 00:03:24.050
aquarium species.

00:03:24.050 --> 00:03:26.640
And so you'll get these crystal
clear shots, which if

00:03:26.640 --> 00:03:29.440
anyone says was taken in the
wild generally are taken at

00:03:29.440 --> 00:03:30.910
the aquarium.

00:03:30.910 --> 00:03:34.190
Loggerheads we see down in
Belize but are actually one of

00:03:34.190 --> 00:03:37.370
the main turtles on the
southeast US coast.

00:03:37.370 --> 00:03:40.640
Most of the nesting and a lot
of loggerhead habitat is in

00:03:40.640 --> 00:03:41.620
the Southeast US.

00:03:41.620 --> 00:03:43.690
So the United States government
and a lot of

00:03:43.690 --> 00:03:46.470
community organizations in
Florida, Carolinas, throughout

00:03:46.470 --> 00:03:49.310
the Gulf, have a big role
in the conservation

00:03:49.310 --> 00:03:50.970
of loggerhead turtles.

00:03:50.970 --> 00:03:53.560
Of course, the Caribbean plays
an important role as well.

00:03:53.560 --> 00:03:55.260
They use the Caribbean
grounds.

00:03:55.260 --> 00:03:57.430
But in some ways, the Caribbean
experiences the

00:03:57.430 --> 00:04:03.120
benefits or costs of good
or poor US management.

00:04:03.120 --> 00:04:06.350
You may see some loggerheads
down at Glover's, but it's not

00:04:06.350 --> 00:04:08.560
necessarily the dominant
species.

00:04:08.560 --> 00:04:11.800
One of the biggest impact for
loggerheads is by catch and

00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:13.020
trawl nets.

00:04:13.020 --> 00:04:14.870
You've probably heard a lot
in the news of trawl nets

00:04:14.870 --> 00:04:16.220
scraping over the bottom.

00:04:16.220 --> 00:04:19.649
US has done quite a lot, and
other countries as well, to

00:04:19.649 --> 00:04:22.500
try to design nets that
don't catch turtles.

00:04:22.500 --> 00:04:23.890
But still, there's quite
a lot of damage.

00:04:23.890 --> 00:04:26.940
And just recently, I think
there's a lawsuit launched on

00:04:26.940 --> 00:04:30.410
the West Coast here in
California on loggerhead

00:04:30.410 --> 00:04:33.380
mortalities for the Pacific
population.

00:04:33.380 --> 00:04:34.880
Because they think about
1,000 a year are

00:04:34.880 --> 00:04:36.530
killed in net drownings.

00:04:36.530 --> 00:04:38.940
Turtles breathe air, so if they
get dragged under for too

00:04:38.940 --> 00:04:40.820
long, they drown and die.

00:04:40.820 --> 00:04:44.200
So anyway, the Northwest
Atlantic loggerhead might see.

00:04:44.200 --> 00:04:47.780
The second one is the green
turtle, one of the largest

00:04:47.780 --> 00:04:50.240
turtle populations
historically.

00:04:50.240 --> 00:04:52.710
Historically, green turtle
populations were 30 to 90

00:04:52.710 --> 00:04:55.940
million individuals in the
Caribbean population,

00:04:55.940 --> 00:04:57.500
Caribbean and Western
Atlantic.

00:04:57.500 --> 00:05:00.440
And now they're down to less
than 300,000 is the estimate.

00:05:00.440 --> 00:05:03.250
We don't absolutely know,
because there's not a perfect

00:05:03.250 --> 00:05:04.900
annual turtle census.

00:05:04.900 --> 00:05:07.100
But this is massive orders
of magnitude.

00:05:07.100 --> 00:05:12.130
So sort of post-Columbus surveys
coming in say that

00:05:12.130 --> 00:05:14.310
green turtles were just
everywhere as far as the eye

00:05:14.310 --> 00:05:16.620
could see, similar to what you
think about as cod up on the

00:05:16.620 --> 00:05:17.740
East Coast or some
of the salmon

00:05:17.740 --> 00:05:18.950
fisheries you have here.

00:05:18.950 --> 00:05:20.410
Just massive quantities.

00:05:20.410 --> 00:05:23.440
But the big problem with
green turtles is they

00:05:23.440 --> 00:05:24.870
taste really good.

00:05:24.870 --> 00:05:27.170
Green turtles eat sea grass.

00:05:27.170 --> 00:05:29.510
They're the only fully
herbivorous sea turtle.

00:05:29.510 --> 00:05:32.700
And they're consumed
by populations

00:05:32.700 --> 00:05:34.450
for hundreds of years.

00:05:34.450 --> 00:05:37.670
They're also very easy to keep
alive on colonial ships and

00:05:37.670 --> 00:05:38.760
trading ships.

00:05:38.760 --> 00:05:41.420
You simply turn them upside
down and you can keep on

00:05:41.420 --> 00:05:43.830
feeding them and keep them alive
for a very long time.

00:05:43.830 --> 00:05:47.400
So green turtle populations were
decimated historically,

00:05:47.400 --> 00:05:51.750
and then even in some places
until the present day.

00:05:51.750 --> 00:05:54.730
This photo is of a green turtle
on sea grass beds,

00:05:54.730 --> 00:05:57.800
which is where the dominant
green turtle habitat is.

00:05:57.800 --> 00:06:00.330
So usually you'll see green
turtles on sea grass beds.

00:06:00.330 --> 00:06:02.460
But you'll also see them
at Glover's Reef.

00:06:02.460 --> 00:06:05.130
And so it's our second-most
common turtle that we have out

00:06:05.130 --> 00:06:08.420
there in the atoll.

00:06:08.420 --> 00:06:13.090
And then, the most iconic turtle
for coral reefs is a

00:06:13.090 --> 00:06:14.240
hawksbill turtle.

00:06:14.240 --> 00:06:16.920
And this is a turtle that's also
known-- you'll see turtle

00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:19.370
shells in general are quite
charismatic, but particularly

00:06:19.370 --> 00:06:21.530
the hawksbill shell was used
for turtle jewelry.

00:06:21.530 --> 00:06:23.880
And still in some places
today, even though it's

00:06:23.880 --> 00:06:27.140
illegal, is used for
turtle jewelry.

00:06:27.140 --> 00:06:29.760
They feed over 90% on sponges.

00:06:29.760 --> 00:06:31.200
So they're feeding on
sponges on those

00:06:31.200 --> 00:06:32.065
reefs, those big, barrel--

00:06:32.065 --> 00:06:34.350
They eat all the different
colors and shapes and sizes

00:06:34.350 --> 00:06:36.540
you see on coral reefs.

00:06:36.540 --> 00:06:39.840
And their populations as well--
estimates range from

00:06:39.840 --> 00:06:42.510
the sort of pre-contact
populations of half a million

00:06:42.510 --> 00:06:44.570
to 1.5 million in
the Caribbean.

00:06:44.570 --> 00:06:47.380
So in order of magnitude,
less than green turtles.

00:06:47.380 --> 00:06:50.770
But now they're thinking about
12,000 nesting females of

00:06:50.770 --> 00:06:53.040
hawksbills in the entire
Caribbean right now.

00:06:53.040 --> 00:06:56.690
So when you see a hawksbill,
that's a few blocks of the

00:06:56.690 --> 00:06:58.140
city of San Francisco.

00:06:58.140 --> 00:07:01.370
12,000 individual female
nesting hawksbills.

00:07:01.370 --> 00:07:03.310
So very small population.

00:07:03.310 --> 00:07:05.780
But you do see quite a
few at Glover's Reef.

00:07:05.780 --> 00:07:08.480
And interestingly, it's a lot
of juveniles that are there.

00:07:08.480 --> 00:07:11.170
So it's a quite important
habitat for a life stage.

00:07:11.170 --> 00:07:14.350
And it also lets you, as you
see Winnie hugging the

00:07:14.350 --> 00:07:16.530
hawksbill, they don't actually
look too big when you see them

00:07:16.530 --> 00:07:19.360
there, because they can be
close to a little over a

00:07:19.360 --> 00:07:23.480
quarter of a meter when they
first come and arrive.

00:07:23.480 --> 00:07:26.820
But primarily being focused
on coral reefs as well.

00:07:26.820 --> 00:07:28.790
I didn't mention about green
turtles-- green turtle nesting

00:07:28.790 --> 00:07:29.880
is huge in the Caribbean.

00:07:29.880 --> 00:07:32.910
Tortuguero in Costa Rica is
maybe a place a lot of people

00:07:32.910 --> 00:07:35.290
have heard of, has historically
been a very

00:07:35.290 --> 00:07:38.130
important nesting ground for
green turtles and has been

00:07:38.130 --> 00:07:40.020
very successful there.

00:07:40.020 --> 00:07:43.450
And hawksbills tend to nest in
a lot more sporadic areas.

00:07:43.450 --> 00:07:45.980
So even the smallest of islands
in Belize and other

00:07:45.980 --> 00:07:48.920
places in the Caribbean can
be quite important for

00:07:48.920 --> 00:07:49.560
hawksbills.

00:07:49.560 --> 00:07:51.580
They nest all over
the Caribbean.

00:07:51.580 --> 00:07:54.080
So these are the three species
that you'll see

00:07:54.080 --> 00:07:55.370
when you're out there.

00:07:55.370 --> 00:07:57.740
Of course, many other people
know of leatherbacks, olive

00:07:57.740 --> 00:07:58.610
ridleys, Kemp's ridleys.

00:07:58.610 --> 00:08:01.020
There's a number of other
species that are out there.

00:08:01.020 --> 00:08:02.600
These are the ones
that you see.

00:08:02.600 --> 00:08:05.220
And of all of them, the
hawksbill is the most

00:08:05.220 --> 00:08:06.950
threatened out at
Glover's Reef.

00:08:06.950 --> 00:08:08.880
And for that reason,
it's a big priority

00:08:08.880 --> 00:08:12.450
for WCS right now.

00:08:12.450 --> 00:08:16.110
So what makes the turtles
so vulnerable?

00:08:16.110 --> 00:08:18.880
There's the issue of the
historic catch, and I'll talk

00:08:18.880 --> 00:08:20.280
about it in a little bit.

00:08:20.280 --> 00:08:22.790
One of them is they have this
life stage that makes them

00:08:22.790 --> 00:08:25.870
incredibly accessible but
incredibly vulnerable.

00:08:25.870 --> 00:08:27.690
So we all know of nesting
turtle beaches.

00:08:27.690 --> 00:08:30.950
And one of the biggest successes
in the amount of

00:08:30.950 --> 00:08:32.630
effort we put out there
to protect turtles.

00:08:32.630 --> 00:08:35.750
This is a turtle nesting in
South Water Caye, just west of

00:08:35.750 --> 00:08:38.730
Glover's Reef, so a little
closer to the mainland.

00:08:38.730 --> 00:08:40.830
And it's a hawksbill laying
its eggs in the sand.

00:08:40.830 --> 00:08:42.730
But right at that moment of
nesting, there's a number of

00:08:42.730 --> 00:08:43.799
different things that
can happen.

00:08:43.799 --> 00:08:47.700
You can take the turtle and
eat it in some places.

00:08:47.700 --> 00:08:48.700
The eggs can be crushed.

00:08:48.700 --> 00:08:51.740
The eggs can be predated
on by other animals.

00:08:51.740 --> 00:08:54.870
And beaches can be used
for development.

00:08:54.870 --> 00:08:55.680
Lots of lights can go up.

00:08:55.680 --> 00:08:57.810
So the nesting process for
turtles has made them

00:08:57.810 --> 00:08:58.800
incredibly vulnerable.

00:08:58.800 --> 00:09:01.940
That explains a lot
of the loss.

00:09:01.940 --> 00:09:05.070
Once they get out, as probably
most of you know--

00:09:05.070 --> 00:09:07.460
this is bigger than life
size right here.

00:09:07.460 --> 00:09:09.000
So when they first come out,
they're very small.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:11.560
This is a baby hawksbill
actually off of our program in

00:09:11.560 --> 00:09:14.720
Nicaragua where we protect a
great number of hawksbill

00:09:14.720 --> 00:09:17.820
nesting beaches in the
Pearl Keys on the

00:09:17.820 --> 00:09:19.640
Caribbean coast of Nicaragua.

00:09:19.640 --> 00:09:24.250
And a typical clutch will put
out a little over 100 eggs,

00:09:24.250 --> 00:09:26.980
but only about 1% of those will
survive, because as they

00:09:26.980 --> 00:09:29.130
come out in the water, they're
extremely vulnerable.

00:09:29.130 --> 00:09:31.790
How many people have been to
turtle nesting beaches and

00:09:31.790 --> 00:09:33.730
seen this either on vacation?

00:09:33.730 --> 00:09:35.840
And then how many people
have seen it on TV?

00:09:35.840 --> 00:09:36.070
OK, right.

00:09:36.070 --> 00:09:38.090
So you've all sort of
got a sense of it.

00:09:38.090 --> 00:09:39.710
If you haven't seen it, one
of these times when

00:09:39.710 --> 00:09:40.830
you're in the tropics--

00:09:40.830 --> 00:09:43.150
and usually you've got to go out
late at night-- it's very

00:09:43.150 --> 00:09:45.780
much worth your while to go
check out a nesting beach and

00:09:45.780 --> 00:09:47.830
see that act of either a turtle
laying their eggs or

00:09:47.830 --> 00:09:50.010
the hatchlings being released.

00:09:50.010 --> 00:09:53.670
But this second part of their
life stage or wherever you

00:09:53.670 --> 00:09:55.000
[INAUDIBLE] also incredibly
vulnerable.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:57.750
Not only the getting off the
beach and getting out into the

00:09:57.750 --> 00:10:00.610
ocean, but then they're
essentially floating around in

00:10:00.610 --> 00:10:01.980
the middle of the ocean
for a while in

00:10:01.980 --> 00:10:03.130
these convergent zones.

00:10:03.130 --> 00:10:06.220
So the Sargasso Sea in the
Atlantic is quite important,

00:10:06.220 --> 00:10:10.300
because a lot of marine life
aggregates there in their

00:10:10.300 --> 00:10:11.620
developmental stages.

00:10:11.620 --> 00:10:13.460
And they're just going to float
around there until they

00:10:13.460 --> 00:10:16.270
get to be about 20 or
25 centimeters.

00:10:16.270 --> 00:10:18.710
And then they'll swim back to
some feeding grounds where

00:10:18.710 --> 00:10:19.780
they can survive.

00:10:19.780 --> 00:10:24.290
So you have a very vulnerable
strategy for them as well,

00:10:24.290 --> 00:10:29.090
which they're in trouble with
just natural predators.

00:10:29.090 --> 00:10:32.350
But then when we bring in human
impacts-- so this is a

00:10:32.350 --> 00:10:37.600
historic map of St. George's
Caye in 1764 recreated for a

00:10:37.600 --> 00:10:39.260
publication in the 1960s.

00:10:39.260 --> 00:10:40.610
And I'm not sure if you
can read it there.

00:10:40.610 --> 00:10:42.910
But on this map of this small
settlement, there was a

00:10:42.910 --> 00:10:43.960
trading post--

00:10:43.960 --> 00:10:47.030
are a bunch of turtle corrals,
so places where they brought

00:10:47.030 --> 00:10:50.030
the green turtles in and kept
them until traders came and

00:10:50.030 --> 00:10:51.560
they could sell them.

00:10:51.560 --> 00:10:53.550
It's estimated that
for about 200

00:10:53.550 --> 00:10:55.790
years in Belize's history--

00:10:55.790 --> 00:10:58.730
which was British Honduras
at the time--

00:10:58.730 --> 00:11:02.140
turtles was the primary fishery,
the primary marine

00:11:02.140 --> 00:11:05.350
economic engine of the colony,
which is not something that

00:11:05.350 --> 00:11:07.570
even enters our mind today that
sea turtles could be the

00:11:07.570 --> 00:11:10.450
primary driver of economic
activity.

00:11:10.450 --> 00:11:14.540
So this historic hunt and
harvest of turtles was a big

00:11:14.540 --> 00:11:15.990
part of the decimation.

00:11:15.990 --> 00:11:19.110
And then still in the 1960s,
people were actively and

00:11:19.110 --> 00:11:21.900
legally harvesting in
Belize, in this

00:11:21.900 --> 00:11:23.410
case, loggerhead turtles.

00:11:23.410 --> 00:11:25.470
They have a bunch of loggerheads
stashed up, and

00:11:25.470 --> 00:11:27.240
then cleaning out
the carcasses.

00:11:27.240 --> 00:11:30.810
Turtles are going to take
anywhere from 30 to 50 years

00:11:30.810 --> 00:11:32.730
to have their first clutch.

00:11:32.730 --> 00:11:36.190
So things that happened in the
'60s, '70s, and '80s are still

00:11:36.190 --> 00:11:38.500
having their impact today.

00:11:38.500 --> 00:11:39.990
A one-year commitment
to turtles

00:11:39.990 --> 00:11:40.870
doesn't really mean anything.

00:11:40.870 --> 00:11:42.640
A 10-year commitment to turtles
doesn't mean anything.

00:11:42.640 --> 00:11:45.370
It's a very long-term commitment
to start seeing the

00:11:45.370 --> 00:11:47.310
results of your actions
take place.

00:11:47.310 --> 00:11:50.240
But this historic meat-first
meat harvest.

00:11:50.240 --> 00:11:54.110
And then in the Victorian Age,
in the late 1800s, turtles

00:11:54.110 --> 00:11:55.580
started to be used
for jewelry.

00:11:55.580 --> 00:11:58.270
So the hawksbill shell was
starting to become a prize

00:11:58.270 --> 00:12:01.760
jewelry until fabricated
materials

00:12:01.760 --> 00:12:03.250
started to replace them.

00:12:03.250 --> 00:12:06.290
So that played a significant
contribution.

00:12:06.290 --> 00:12:08.770
You see some examples of the
hawksbill jewelry, which you

00:12:08.770 --> 00:12:09.630
say, oh yeah, I bought
sunglasses

00:12:09.630 --> 00:12:10.760
that look like that.

00:12:10.760 --> 00:12:16.330
So the pattern imprint of
hawksbill shells are still in

00:12:16.330 --> 00:12:18.190
our fashion design
sense today.

00:12:18.190 --> 00:12:19.730
Or maybe a barrette you have.

00:12:19.730 --> 00:12:22.110
Even though, most likely, most
of that that you have now or

00:12:22.110 --> 00:12:24.730
hopefully what you have now,
unless it was passed on from

00:12:24.730 --> 00:12:27.820
grandparents, is not from
hawksbill shells.

00:12:27.820 --> 00:12:30.790
But you see the volume of
carapaces that can be

00:12:30.790 --> 00:12:32.620
collected for this
type of trade.

00:12:32.620 --> 00:12:36.150
And then also, this is actually
a photo from only the

00:12:36.150 --> 00:12:39.480
last 10 years in Nicaragua where
direct harvesting of

00:12:39.480 --> 00:12:44.040
eggs takes place just to eat
the eggs directly, not to

00:12:44.040 --> 00:12:45.490
raise them up or anything
like that.

00:12:45.490 --> 00:12:50.180
So a number of different uses of
the shell and the products

00:12:50.180 --> 00:12:52.790
of the turtle.

00:12:52.790 --> 00:12:55.250
So we talked about the historic
hunt of sea turtles.

00:12:55.250 --> 00:12:58.720
But just to continue to paint a
grimmer and grimmer picture

00:12:58.720 --> 00:13:01.180
for what, frankly, in marine
conservation is something that

00:13:01.180 --> 00:13:04.000
we've done a lot of
good things for.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:05.120
But it's just important
to recognize

00:13:05.120 --> 00:13:06.770
that this is happening.

00:13:06.770 --> 00:13:09.370
Still in the Caribbean, there
are legal hunts of turtles

00:13:09.370 --> 00:13:10.470
going on today.

00:13:10.470 --> 00:13:13.160
And then, as I think probably
most of you know, turtles are

00:13:13.160 --> 00:13:14.610
swimming throughout
all the countries.

00:13:14.610 --> 00:13:18.070
So a turtle we find in Belize
one year might be over in Cuba

00:13:18.070 --> 00:13:19.230
later on in its life stage.

00:13:19.230 --> 00:13:20.930
And it may have been born
in the Windward

00:13:20.930 --> 00:13:21.770
Islands in the Caribbean.

00:13:21.770 --> 00:13:24.150
So they're moving around
quite a bit.

00:13:24.150 --> 00:13:27.020
But these are photos from our
program in Nicaragua where

00:13:27.020 --> 00:13:31.200
it's estimated still about
10,000 green turtles are taken

00:13:31.200 --> 00:13:35.210
a year in a traditional harvest,
not for export but

00:13:35.210 --> 00:13:36.440
for meat consumption.

00:13:36.440 --> 00:13:38.780
So there's still a great amount
of pressure on sea

00:13:38.780 --> 00:13:40.250
turtles today.

00:13:42.760 --> 00:13:43.870
The expression--

00:13:43.870 --> 00:13:45.360
I just thought I would mention
it here, though it's a little

00:13:45.360 --> 00:13:46.500
bit morbid to say it--

00:13:46.500 --> 00:13:49.370
of turning turtle comes from
once you turn a turtle over,

00:13:49.370 --> 00:13:50.760
they can still survive,
obviously,

00:13:50.760 --> 00:13:51.520
for a very long time.

00:13:51.520 --> 00:13:53.380
They're still breathing air.

00:13:53.380 --> 00:13:55.260
This is how they'd be
transported on ships across

00:13:55.260 --> 00:13:56.400
the ocean for their meat.

00:13:56.400 --> 00:13:58.700
They would stay fresh,
but they weren't

00:13:58.700 --> 00:14:00.510
going to be going anywhere.

00:14:00.510 --> 00:14:03.290
And then finally, like I
mentioned with the loggerheads

00:14:03.290 --> 00:14:05.070
earlier, the issue of bycatch
is something you

00:14:05.070 --> 00:14:07.000
hear quite a bit--

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:09.570
turtles getting caught
up in shrimp trawls.

00:14:09.570 --> 00:14:12.640
Any type of bottom trawl is
catching the same things that

00:14:12.640 --> 00:14:13.680
turtles are eating.

00:14:13.680 --> 00:14:16.060
So those are big opportunities
for turtles to be taken up in

00:14:16.060 --> 00:14:17.080
those trawls.

00:14:17.080 --> 00:14:18.490
A lot has been done.

00:14:18.490 --> 00:14:21.440
Turtle exclusion devices or TEDs
have been innovated to

00:14:21.440 --> 00:14:24.900
try to inhibit the amount of
turtles that are taken up.

00:14:24.900 --> 00:14:27.210
But still, as long as you're
fishing on the sea floor,

00:14:27.210 --> 00:14:29.130
there's a good chance
that you could be

00:14:29.130 --> 00:14:32.490
collecting marine turtles.

00:14:32.490 --> 00:14:35.550
Sometimes you think about
wildlife conservation or any

00:14:35.550 --> 00:14:38.400
type of conservation, and
there's one major thing you

00:14:38.400 --> 00:14:39.530
have to do.

00:14:39.530 --> 00:14:42.160
And you can potentially, if you
do that one major thing

00:14:42.160 --> 00:14:45.970
like create a protected area
or stop the trade in ivory,

00:14:45.970 --> 00:14:47.780
then maybe that's going to make
a significant difference.

00:14:47.780 --> 00:14:50.550
And with turtles, there's just
all these different components

00:14:50.550 --> 00:14:52.510
to the threats that have
happened through different

00:14:52.510 --> 00:14:54.490
timelines that are also
happening with different

00:14:54.490 --> 00:14:55.770
constituencies.

00:14:55.770 --> 00:14:59.836
And what I would like to do next
is move towards some of

00:14:59.836 --> 00:15:00.840
the optimism side.

00:15:00.840 --> 00:15:03.380
So a lot of this stuff has
happened in the past.

00:15:03.380 --> 00:15:06.800
And now there's a patchwork, but
internally, increasingly

00:15:06.800 --> 00:15:11.340
turning into a considerable
amount of effort by WCS of one

00:15:11.340 --> 00:15:15.240
of many groups that is out there
helping to save turtles

00:15:15.240 --> 00:15:16.370
and protect turtles.

00:15:16.370 --> 00:15:18.620
And a lot of governments that
are out there as well.

00:15:18.620 --> 00:15:21.390
And Belize is really an
interesting story and where

00:15:21.390 --> 00:15:24.760
the work we're going to talk
about at the end comes in is

00:15:24.760 --> 00:15:27.850
an interesting time in the
history of protecting turtles,

00:15:27.850 --> 00:15:28.990
essentially.

00:15:28.990 --> 00:15:32.990
So here's a review that was done
by Piniak and Eckert two

00:15:32.990 --> 00:15:34.790
years ago just looking
at how turtles are

00:15:34.790 --> 00:15:36.220
protected in the Caribbean.

00:15:36.220 --> 00:15:41.120
The gray areas are complete
protection.

00:15:41.120 --> 00:15:44.290
The dotted areas are protected
with some exceptions.

00:15:44.290 --> 00:15:46.980
Most of those exceptions are for
traditional or artisanal

00:15:46.980 --> 00:15:49.510
or customary type hunts.

00:15:49.510 --> 00:15:52.600
Those could vary from the
Nicaragua case of being

00:15:52.600 --> 00:15:55.690
thousands and thousands of
turtles to only a few turtles

00:15:55.690 --> 00:15:58.460
taken every year in some
jurisdictions.

00:15:58.460 --> 00:16:00.660
And then you have, actually,
full legal fisheries still

00:16:00.660 --> 00:16:03.280
happening in some countries
as well.

00:16:03.280 --> 00:16:07.570
So even though some parts of
turtle exploitation are

00:16:07.570 --> 00:16:10.010
well-governed and protected,
there's still a patchwork of

00:16:10.010 --> 00:16:10.770
management.

00:16:10.770 --> 00:16:13.300
And as I mentioned before,
turtles are going to move

00:16:13.300 --> 00:16:16.060
between jurisdictions
quite a lot.

00:16:16.060 --> 00:16:18.890
This, by the way, are the
exclusive economic zones of

00:16:18.890 --> 00:16:22.240
countries out to 200 nautical
miles or the halfway point

00:16:22.240 --> 00:16:25.160
between countries if they abutt
each other, as they do

00:16:25.160 --> 00:16:28.130
in the Caribbean.

00:16:28.130 --> 00:16:32.370
But Belize, in many ways, has
come almost full circle.

00:16:32.370 --> 00:16:34.440
It was on the map as under full
protection, because there

00:16:34.440 --> 00:16:37.420
is still the potential for an
exception for customary take,

00:16:37.420 --> 00:16:39.330
although it's not used.

00:16:39.330 --> 00:16:41.750
Has come the whole way in terms
of turtle protection,

00:16:41.750 --> 00:16:44.130
such that now, the Fisheries
Department of Belize, who

00:16:44.130 --> 00:16:46.970
you'll be working with when
you're there on the trip, is

00:16:46.970 --> 00:16:49.850
taking care of turtles,
untangling them from gear.

00:16:49.850 --> 00:16:53.240
And if anyone ever were to be
harvesting turtles, has a

00:16:53.240 --> 00:16:56.350
relatively robust enforcement
effort out there protecting

00:16:56.350 --> 00:16:58.140
for a number of different
marine things.

00:16:58.140 --> 00:17:00.900
So the Fisheries Department of
Belize, the country of Belize

00:17:00.900 --> 00:17:04.970
has come quite a long way from
historically, when that was

00:17:04.970 --> 00:17:08.200
the dominant part of
their economy.

00:17:08.200 --> 00:17:10.500
Just to trace it back a little
bit, the first efforts to

00:17:10.500 --> 00:17:14.700
protect turtles in Belize
were in the late '70s.

00:17:14.700 --> 00:17:17.920
Under the Wildlife Act, there
was an attempt to protect

00:17:17.920 --> 00:17:19.780
turtles fully.

00:17:19.780 --> 00:17:24.210
But it conflicted with the
Fisheries Department that was

00:17:24.210 --> 00:17:27.560
trying to have some sort of
catch controls and managing

00:17:27.560 --> 00:17:28.430
the harvest.

00:17:28.430 --> 00:17:31.780
So really, for the late '70s all
the way through the '80s,

00:17:31.780 --> 00:17:35.810
there was still ongoing
take-and-harvest of turtles.

00:17:35.810 --> 00:17:38.690
Another effort was made in the
early '90s that was a full

00:17:38.690 --> 00:17:40.690
protection of hawksbill
turtles.

00:17:40.690 --> 00:17:43.090
If you remember from the
beginning, now we're talking

00:17:43.090 --> 00:17:45.910
only about 12,000 nesting
females today in the Caribbean

00:17:45.910 --> 00:17:49.280
of hawksbill, so extremely
vulnerable.

00:17:49.280 --> 00:17:52.630
So a full protection of
hawksbill and then size limits

00:17:52.630 --> 00:17:56.270
for other turtles happened
in the early '90s.

00:17:56.270 --> 00:17:59.620
And it wasn't until 2002 that
Belize put in the full

00:17:59.620 --> 00:18:01.810
protection for all species
of turtles.

00:18:01.810 --> 00:18:05.640
But now, I don't know how much
you talk to people who are

00:18:05.640 --> 00:18:08.020
working in conservation, but you
hear about what the real

00:18:08.020 --> 00:18:10.320
law is and then what the reality
is on the ground.

00:18:10.320 --> 00:18:11.660
And it's taken quite
a long time.

00:18:11.660 --> 00:18:14.980
But now, for the most part,
most turtle harvesting the

00:18:14.980 --> 00:18:16.990
people have heard about
in Belize has stopped.

00:18:16.990 --> 00:18:21.890
So for three decades, there's
been this slow wrench-down on

00:18:21.890 --> 00:18:24.570
turtle harvesting to the point
where it's quite rare today.

00:18:24.570 --> 00:18:26.830
You still have entanglements or
things where they'll need

00:18:26.830 --> 00:18:29.500
to be freed, but there's not a
direct and there isn't too

00:18:29.500 --> 00:18:33.180
much of any sort of black market
activity going on.

00:18:33.180 --> 00:18:36.690
Interestingly, Belize, because
it was part of the British

00:18:36.690 --> 00:18:39.270
government when CITES, the
Convention on International

00:18:39.270 --> 00:18:42.730
Trade in Endangered Species,
stopped trade in turtle

00:18:42.730 --> 00:18:46.510
exploitation around the world
that was signed in the '70s

00:18:46.510 --> 00:18:49.150
when Belize was still
part of the UK.

00:18:49.150 --> 00:18:52.750
And so when Belize declared its
independence afterwards,

00:18:52.750 --> 00:18:54.850
there was a sort of a convenient
ignoring of the

00:18:54.850 --> 00:19:00.180
fact that they had signed
it when they

00:19:00.180 --> 00:19:01.200
were part of Britain.

00:19:01.200 --> 00:19:03.230
And so it was not actually
in effect until the

00:19:03.230 --> 00:19:04.670
late '80s for Belize.

00:19:04.670 --> 00:19:08.920
So the Japanese imports of
hawksbill turtle carapaces and

00:19:08.920 --> 00:19:11.480
turtle products in the '80s
were still spiking quite

00:19:11.480 --> 00:19:13.060
considerably from Belize.

00:19:13.060 --> 00:19:15.890
So there's still these pulses
in the '80s while wildlife

00:19:15.890 --> 00:19:18.590
protection measures are trying
to happen on the ground, not

00:19:18.590 --> 00:19:20.180
having the impact
that they have.

00:19:20.180 --> 00:19:23.760
But today, turtles are
quite protected.

00:19:23.760 --> 00:19:26.310
Belize also leads as one
of the most robust

00:19:26.310 --> 00:19:28.350
marine-protected area
systems on the

00:19:28.350 --> 00:19:29.520
Mesoamerican Barrier Reef.

00:19:29.520 --> 00:19:31.140
So this is a map of Belize.

00:19:31.140 --> 00:19:34.170
The Barrier Reef is on the
east side right there.

00:19:34.170 --> 00:19:36.580
You can see it extending all
the way down from Bacalar

00:19:36.580 --> 00:19:38.530
Chico to Sapodilla Keys.

00:19:38.530 --> 00:19:41.000
Glover's Reef is just
the offshore atoll.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:45.140
You can see it's all in green,
meaning it's all part of a

00:19:45.140 --> 00:19:46.310
marine reserve.

00:19:46.310 --> 00:19:48.340
And so the government of Belize
not only has been

00:19:48.340 --> 00:19:50.920
protecting turtles but is
increasingly protecting a

00:19:50.920 --> 00:19:56.000
number species, setting aside
areas for no fishing zones,

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:58.150
and creating a number
of different places.

00:19:58.150 --> 00:20:06.330
And just about a month ago,
Turneffe Atoll right here was

00:20:06.330 --> 00:20:09.480
just declared as the newest
marine reserve in Belize.

00:20:09.480 --> 00:20:11.660
So the government is continuing
to advance not only

00:20:11.660 --> 00:20:14.530
protection of turtles but the
entire marine ecosystem.

00:20:14.530 --> 00:20:16.770
Which when you think about all
those different impacts, is

00:20:16.770 --> 00:20:19.165
what it's going to take
to conserve turtles.

00:20:21.740 --> 00:20:25.810
So just a quick background of
WCS in Belize to get us to the

00:20:25.810 --> 00:20:28.510
point where we'll talk
about the trip that

00:20:28.510 --> 00:20:29.510
we're thinking about.

00:20:29.510 --> 00:20:33.270
This is an aerial view of
Glover's Reef atoll where now

00:20:33.270 --> 00:20:35.110
one of our base of
operations is.

00:20:35.110 --> 00:20:38.810
WCS has been operating in Belize
since the early 1980s.

00:20:38.810 --> 00:20:41.720
And we worked to help declare
some of the first marine

00:20:41.720 --> 00:20:44.190
reserves or the first marine
reserve in Belize--

00:20:44.190 --> 00:20:48.250
Hol Chan Marine Reserve has
since moved on to help manage

00:20:48.250 --> 00:20:51.620
Glover's Reef, South Water
Caye, and to helping the

00:20:51.620 --> 00:20:53.230
government of Belize and a
number of their different

00:20:53.230 --> 00:20:55.350
measures, historically,
to protect

00:20:55.350 --> 00:20:58.010
turtles, to reform fisheries.

00:20:58.010 --> 00:21:00.300
We have a large program to work
on shark conservation

00:21:00.300 --> 00:21:01.060
throughout Belize.

00:21:01.060 --> 00:21:03.800
So we're doing quite a lot in
Belize to help manage the

00:21:03.800 --> 00:21:04.450
marine environment.

00:21:04.450 --> 00:21:08.090
Belize, as you probably know,
is a global priority for

00:21:08.090 --> 00:21:10.790
marine conservation, because it
sits on a very biodiverse

00:21:10.790 --> 00:21:14.070
Mesoamerican Barrier Reef.

00:21:14.070 --> 00:21:17.280
We have about 20 staff in
country, a lot of them out on

00:21:17.280 --> 00:21:19.715
the station, some of them in
Belize City that you'll meet

00:21:19.715 --> 00:21:23.720
as well, most of them Belizean
who are working to

00:21:23.720 --> 00:21:25.530
conserve the area.

00:21:25.530 --> 00:21:28.190
Just a few shots of some of the
other things that exist.

00:21:28.190 --> 00:21:30.220
So we're talking about turtles,
but other really

00:21:30.220 --> 00:21:34.310
important species and iconic
species that are out there on

00:21:34.310 --> 00:21:35.100
the reef as well.

00:21:35.100 --> 00:21:37.040
Anyone know what these are?

00:21:37.040 --> 00:21:37.995
Gander?

00:21:37.995 --> 00:21:38.390
Failure.

00:21:38.390 --> 00:21:39.055
No.

00:21:39.055 --> 00:21:40.230
So they're Nassau grouper.

00:21:40.230 --> 00:21:42.440
You can tell by this little
spot back here.

00:21:42.440 --> 00:21:44.730
And Nassau grouper are
ecologically extinct

00:21:44.730 --> 00:21:46.570
throughout a lot of
the Caribbean.

00:21:46.570 --> 00:21:49.590
They have this unfortunate
habit, similar to turtles, of

00:21:49.590 --> 00:21:51.950
coming together at part of their
life stage where they

00:21:51.950 --> 00:21:52.810
become really vulnerable.

00:21:52.810 --> 00:21:54.260
They come together to spawn.

00:21:54.260 --> 00:21:56.720
Historically, fishermen have
decided to put nets around or

00:21:56.720 --> 00:21:58.540
hooks and catch them.

00:21:58.540 --> 00:22:00.790
But we do quite a lot throughout
Belize to protect

00:22:00.790 --> 00:22:01.770
Nassau groupers.

00:22:01.770 --> 00:22:04.600
And now, all known spawning
aggregations of Nassau

00:22:04.600 --> 00:22:07.350
groupers are protected,
including Northeast Point at

00:22:07.350 --> 00:22:10.190
Glover's Reef, which has a big
spawning event in February,

00:22:10.190 --> 00:22:11.890
March every year.

00:22:11.890 --> 00:22:14.860
Belize has cetaceans like a
number of other countries.

00:22:14.860 --> 00:22:16.620
This is actually the
first dive I ever

00:22:16.620 --> 00:22:18.740
took at Glover's Reef.

00:22:18.740 --> 00:22:21.200
And I turned around and heard
the whistling of a beaked and

00:22:21.200 --> 00:22:24.000
bottlenosed dolphin that
just swam right by.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:26.260
There's not any exploitation
with these species going on

00:22:26.260 --> 00:22:28.020
right now, so they're safe.

00:22:28.020 --> 00:22:31.390
But they do obviously have a
historical legacy in they

00:22:31.390 --> 00:22:33.820
change the dynamic of
the environment.

00:22:33.820 --> 00:22:35.910
Elkhorn coral is very
vulnerable.

00:22:35.910 --> 00:22:38.950
It's on the endangered species
list in the US because of

00:22:38.950 --> 00:22:40.360
disease and climate impacts.

00:22:40.360 --> 00:22:42.560
And it's the main reef-building
coral.

00:22:42.560 --> 00:22:45.250
If you see this when you're in
Belize and in the Caribbean in

00:22:45.250 --> 00:22:48.010
general, you're quite lucky,
because a lot of stocks have

00:22:48.010 --> 00:22:51.350
been decimated in the '90s, and
now they're starting to

00:22:51.350 --> 00:22:52.160
come back as well.

00:22:52.160 --> 00:22:55.300
But Elkhorn is one of many
species of coral that is quite

00:22:55.300 --> 00:22:57.735
important and worth thinking
about conserving.

00:23:00.310 --> 00:23:01.630
So here's a shot
of Middle Caye.

00:23:01.630 --> 00:23:05.750
This is the research station
on the north point of the

00:23:05.750 --> 00:23:07.450
island, which is actually
the left side of your

00:23:07.450 --> 00:23:08.520
screen right now.

00:23:08.520 --> 00:23:11.440
The rest of the island is now
being left to restore its

00:23:11.440 --> 00:23:12.790
natural habitat.

00:23:12.790 --> 00:23:15.130
And there's a trail that goes
around the outside.

00:23:15.130 --> 00:23:17.960
This is where we conduct all of
our research operations as

00:23:17.960 --> 00:23:21.200
well as we host the Fisheries
Department that runs all their

00:23:21.200 --> 00:23:23.760
enforcement patrols from
the station as well.

00:23:23.760 --> 00:23:27.000
They have an enforcement tower
as well as a number of

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:29.430
different equipment in their
boat that they can go out to

00:23:29.430 --> 00:23:31.860
look for violations of
the marine reserve.

00:23:31.860 --> 00:23:35.100
And you run into them there
as well on your turtle

00:23:35.100 --> 00:23:36.770
monitoring.

00:23:36.770 --> 00:23:40.340
The station itself has several
dormitories, a galley, the

00:23:40.340 --> 00:23:42.170
Fisheries base classroom.

00:23:42.170 --> 00:23:45.090
We are as solar as we
can possibly be.

00:23:45.090 --> 00:23:47.900
We have a very large solar
array that basically can

00:23:47.900 --> 00:23:50.080
manage the load when
people are there.

00:23:50.080 --> 00:23:53.620
Although we do have backup
generators if the demand is

00:23:53.620 --> 00:23:57.410
really high, if people are using
a lot of electricity.

00:23:57.410 --> 00:23:59.500
We also take all of our water's

00:23:59.500 --> 00:24:03.200
coming off of the roofs.

00:24:03.200 --> 00:24:08.270
The toilets are all compost,
but they smell quite fine.

00:24:08.270 --> 00:24:10.630
As much as possible,
we try to be an

00:24:10.630 --> 00:24:12.960
eco-friendly research station.

00:24:12.960 --> 00:24:15.140
It's great for our mission, and
it's great for the planet.

00:24:15.140 --> 00:24:17.470
It's also the way to
live on islands.

00:24:17.470 --> 00:24:19.750
For any of you that have been
on remote islands or out in

00:24:19.750 --> 00:24:26.390
the remote desert, it just makes
economic sense as well.

00:24:26.390 --> 00:24:29.240
So here's another photo of
the team from last year.

00:24:29.240 --> 00:24:33.530
And going in now to talk about
the surveys that you'll be

00:24:33.530 --> 00:24:35.770
doing in Belize or at least some
of your friends will be

00:24:35.770 --> 00:24:37.196
doing in Belize.

00:24:37.196 --> 00:24:39.550
I think a really important
question is to hear why, with

00:24:39.550 --> 00:24:41.400
everything we talked about,
why is it important to be

00:24:41.400 --> 00:24:43.500
conducting these surveys?

00:24:43.500 --> 00:24:46.900
These are the only in-water
surveys for

00:24:46.900 --> 00:24:48.450
marine turtles in Belize.

00:24:48.450 --> 00:24:50.810
Right now, if you remember, the
hawksbill, which is the

00:24:50.810 --> 00:24:53.630
dominant species we see out
there, is the most critically

00:24:53.630 --> 00:24:55.720
endangered of all the
turtles in Belize as

00:24:55.720 --> 00:24:57.510
well as in the Caribbean.

00:24:57.510 --> 00:25:02.450
There's this long life cycle
issue from when they are born

00:25:02.450 --> 00:25:05.420
to when they start having
offspring as well.

00:25:05.420 --> 00:25:07.930
So if we don't monitor and
learn about what habitat

00:25:07.930 --> 00:25:10.420
they're using, what's happened
to the populations at a number

00:25:10.420 --> 00:25:13.160
of places around the Caribbean,
these species can

00:25:13.160 --> 00:25:15.050
blink out before you necessarily
know it.

00:25:15.050 --> 00:25:18.450
And so at this point in time,
while the population levels

00:25:18.450 --> 00:25:20.470
throughout the Caribbean are at
the bottom of their curve,

00:25:20.470 --> 00:25:23.660
we hope, or potentially still
declining, monitoring simply

00:25:23.660 --> 00:25:26.880
the status of a population,
getting a sense of their size,

00:25:26.880 --> 00:25:29.910
how old are they, getting a
sense of their health, their

00:25:29.910 --> 00:25:32.540
use of the reef, do they
use certain parts

00:25:32.540 --> 00:25:33.490
of areas over others?

00:25:33.490 --> 00:25:35.500
Because if they do, maybe we
should have more protections

00:25:35.500 --> 00:25:38.290
there just to make sure there's
no incidental catch.

00:25:38.290 --> 00:25:40.850
That type of information
is really critical.

00:25:40.850 --> 00:25:43.910
Plus you'll see the Belize
Fisheries Department, some of

00:25:43.910 --> 00:25:47.800
our staff, and some of your
students from local schools

00:25:47.800 --> 00:25:51.180
come out building up national
pride around sea turtles and

00:25:51.180 --> 00:25:53.930
about understanding their
biology and their importance

00:25:53.930 --> 00:25:55.390
is quite strong as well.

00:25:55.390 --> 00:25:58.240
So the sea turtle monitoring
absolutely is a core

00:25:58.240 --> 00:25:59.390
priority for us.

00:25:59.390 --> 00:26:03.480
And the thing that makes this
trip interesting is we need

00:26:03.480 --> 00:26:04.870
the human power to do it.

00:26:04.870 --> 00:26:05.560
We can't do it.

00:26:05.560 --> 00:26:08.180
We only have a few staff on
the station, so we need a

00:26:08.180 --> 00:26:09.330
bunch of people out there.

00:26:09.330 --> 00:26:14.150
As the folks that did it last
year will tell you, it is

00:26:14.150 --> 00:26:14.830
difficult work.

00:26:14.830 --> 00:26:17.400
It's a lot of work out
there swimming.

00:26:17.400 --> 00:26:19.690
But it is what's critical
for us to achieve our

00:26:19.690 --> 00:26:21.060
conservation.

00:26:21.060 --> 00:26:24.580
So I think I'll just
take a moment here.

00:26:24.580 --> 00:26:27.750
This is one of the Belizeans
coming up with a hawksbill.

00:26:27.750 --> 00:26:30.520
The basic idea of the turtle
surveys is we transect the

00:26:30.520 --> 00:26:34.140
entire atoll with a number of
different line transects.

00:26:34.140 --> 00:26:36.790
And you're looking both for
sightings of turtles and then,

00:26:36.790 --> 00:26:39.260
if possible, you're
capturing turtles.

00:26:39.260 --> 00:26:41.920
Not forever, but capturing them
to measure them and to

00:26:41.920 --> 00:26:45.070
take health assessments and a
number of different things.

00:26:45.070 --> 00:26:47.890
Obviously, the capture rate is
quite different than the

00:26:47.890 --> 00:26:48.580
sighting rate.

00:26:48.580 --> 00:26:50.260
And so we're not able
to capture as many

00:26:50.260 --> 00:26:51.880
turtles as we can sight.

00:26:51.880 --> 00:26:53.870
And last year, a few of the
volunteers were able to

00:26:53.870 --> 00:26:55.930
capture some, but we're
still able to

00:26:55.930 --> 00:26:58.580
capture 20 or 30 turtles.

00:26:58.580 --> 00:27:02.750
I guess with this slide up here,
I should ask if someone

00:27:02.750 --> 00:27:05.100
who was here last year maybe
say one or two things about

00:27:05.100 --> 00:27:07.420
the experience out on
the water while

00:27:07.420 --> 00:27:09.040
they were on the trip.

00:27:09.040 --> 00:27:09.920
Want to go for it?

00:27:09.920 --> 00:27:13.920
AUDIENCE: Basically, the
water is amazing.

00:27:13.920 --> 00:27:15.843
So sometimes you'll have really
good visibility, and

00:27:15.843 --> 00:27:21.200
you can actually see the ocean
down to 100-feet deep.

00:27:21.200 --> 00:27:22.810
You can see from the boat
down to the bottom.

00:27:22.810 --> 00:27:25.900
You can see sharks and coral.

00:27:25.900 --> 00:27:29.430
So basically, you're
floating along the

00:27:29.430 --> 00:27:30.870
top looking for turtles.

00:27:30.870 --> 00:27:35.170
And if you spot one, you kind
of raise your hand, and you

00:27:35.170 --> 00:27:40.450
can wait for one of the
Fisheries guys to come help

00:27:40.450 --> 00:27:41.070
you catch it.

00:27:41.070 --> 00:27:44.650
Or you can kind of attempt to
free-dive and catch a turtle.

00:27:44.650 --> 00:27:48.570
But these guys can free-dive
to 75-feet deep, so maybe

00:27:48.570 --> 00:27:52.300
that's kind of a little deep
for your average swimmer.

00:27:52.300 --> 00:27:55.330
But basically, you got to kind
of sneak up behind them if

00:27:55.330 --> 00:27:57.960
they're sitting on the ground.

00:27:57.960 --> 00:27:59.330
Because if they see you,
they'll kind of dart

00:27:59.330 --> 00:28:00.300
off and swim away.

00:28:00.300 --> 00:28:02.620
So you kind of try to come
up behind them and

00:28:02.620 --> 00:28:05.390
kind of grab them.

00:28:05.390 --> 00:28:06.500
So these guys right here--

00:28:06.500 --> 00:28:07.900
I think they're doing
a relay, because the

00:28:07.900 --> 00:28:10.050
turtle is so far down.

00:28:10.050 --> 00:28:12.790
So they would actually grab
it and then pass it off to

00:28:12.790 --> 00:28:15.110
another guy, because they're
holding their breath really

00:28:15.110 --> 00:28:16.450
long and these turtles
are kind of

00:28:16.450 --> 00:28:18.406
fighting for their way.

00:28:18.406 --> 00:28:19.590
You want to add something?

00:28:19.590 --> 00:28:20.502
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:28:20.502 --> 00:28:21.865
It's a bit of teamwork.

00:28:21.865 --> 00:28:22.950
Catching the turtles definitely

00:28:22.950 --> 00:28:24.366
takes a bit of teamwork.

00:28:24.366 --> 00:28:27.900
Often, we'd send one person
to go down and--

00:28:27.900 --> 00:28:30.265
as Elaine was saying, you have
to sneak up on them.

00:28:30.265 --> 00:28:33.480
And you can burn a lot of air
waiting until you grab it and

00:28:33.480 --> 00:28:35.660
then hand it off to somebody
else who's maybe a little

00:28:35.660 --> 00:28:37.610
fresher to swim it up
to the surface.

00:28:37.610 --> 00:28:40.710
And then there's other people
on the boat who take it from

00:28:40.710 --> 00:28:42.790
you as you pull him
out of the water.

00:28:42.790 --> 00:28:46.990
And they are ready with tape
measures and things like that

00:28:46.990 --> 00:28:49.905
to weigh them and tag them.

00:28:49.905 --> 00:28:51.850
AUDIENCE: But it's pretty
amazing, because once you get

00:28:51.850 --> 00:28:55.510
them to the top, we get to do
measurements like how wide

00:28:55.510 --> 00:28:59.040
they are, how long they are, and
take little tissue samples

00:28:59.040 --> 00:29:03.330
for them to send back to a lab
and do analysis on them.

00:29:03.330 --> 00:29:04.930
DR. CALEB MCCLENNEN: Great.

00:29:04.930 --> 00:29:07.390
AUDIENCE: You just have to work
a little bit to focus on

00:29:07.390 --> 00:29:09.320
the task at hand and not get
distracted by all the pretty

00:29:09.320 --> 00:29:10.810
things in the ocean.

00:29:10.810 --> 00:29:13.880
The visibility is ridiculously
good by

00:29:13.880 --> 00:29:16.236
Northern California standards.

00:29:16.236 --> 00:29:16.980
DR. CALEB MCCLENNEN: Great.

00:29:16.980 --> 00:29:18.230
Thanks, guys.

00:29:21.770 --> 00:29:22.860
Yeah, so we do want to
have a sense of that.

00:29:22.860 --> 00:29:26.150
I hope you got that it is some
work as well as fun, but

00:29:26.150 --> 00:29:27.090
there's obviously
some wonderful

00:29:27.090 --> 00:29:27.850
distractions to have.

00:29:27.850 --> 00:29:28.820
Did you have a question?

00:29:28.820 --> 00:29:30.300
AUDIENCE: Yeah, do you
ever use scuba?

00:29:30.300 --> 00:29:30.972
Or it's all--

00:29:30.972 --> 00:29:32.840
DR. CALEB MCCLENNEN: Not for
capturing the turtles.

00:29:32.840 --> 00:29:36.480
So we do do scuba for a number
of the different type of

00:29:36.480 --> 00:29:37.760
surveys that we do
and the research

00:29:37.760 --> 00:29:39.210
we do out at Glover's.

00:29:39.210 --> 00:29:41.390
But not for this, because
you have to bring

00:29:41.390 --> 00:29:42.850
them up to the surface.

00:29:42.850 --> 00:29:45.840
So the decompression issues.

00:29:45.840 --> 00:29:46.295
Yeah?

