00:45:09.120 --> 00:45:12.620
Is there a lot of illegal
fishing or shark finning

00:45:12.620 --> 00:45:14.620
pressures or anything
like that?

00:45:14.620 --> 00:45:16.820
DR. CALEB MCCLENNEN: So most
of the marine reserves in

00:45:16.820 --> 00:45:20.850
Belize, the areas that are part
of the marine reserves,

00:45:20.850 --> 00:45:23.540
almost all the shark fishing
has been effectively

00:45:23.540 --> 00:45:26.370
controlled through a lot of
intense investment and

00:45:26.370 --> 00:45:27.070
enforcement.

00:45:27.070 --> 00:45:29.270
However, it is still
legal to fish shark

00:45:29.270 --> 00:45:30.800
outside of the reserves.

00:45:30.800 --> 00:45:34.100
Within the reserve itself-- so
if this is a marine reserve,

00:45:34.100 --> 00:45:37.080
only a portion, I believe,
is a true no-take zone.

00:45:37.080 --> 00:45:40.380
So in Glover's Reef, it's the
southern portion of the reef

00:45:40.380 --> 00:45:43.490
that is a no-take zone where
there's no fishing whatsoever.

00:45:43.490 --> 00:45:45.360
And then a smaller portion which
is absolute wilderness,

00:45:45.360 --> 00:45:48.190
which is pretty rare
in the ocean.

00:45:48.190 --> 00:45:49.970
Enforcement varies per area.

00:45:49.970 --> 00:45:52.330
So we've been working at
Glover's for a while, and I

00:45:52.330 --> 00:45:54.800
would say I am very biased.

00:45:54.800 --> 00:45:57.210
But if you trust me and I say
I'm being objective, our

00:45:57.210 --> 00:45:59.700
enforcement numbers are very
strong in terms of compliance

00:45:59.700 --> 00:46:00.960
at Glover's Reef right now.

00:46:00.960 --> 00:46:03.510
We've just moved to South
Water Caye, which is the

00:46:03.510 --> 00:46:06.970
biggest reserve in Belize and
has a very large no-take zone.

00:46:06.970 --> 00:46:09.000
And the Fisheries Department is
saying, we need help with

00:46:09.000 --> 00:46:10.520
enforcement, we know there's
infractions.

00:46:10.520 --> 00:46:13.480
And we're trying to figure out
solutions to help them and

00:46:13.480 --> 00:46:15.190
putting more resources
into South Water.

00:46:15.190 --> 00:46:20.590
So it's not perfect, but some
areas are quite well enforced.

00:46:20.590 --> 00:46:23.910
Most of what you see on there as
a marine reserve has people

00:46:23.910 --> 00:46:25.400
on the ground or in the
water that are out

00:46:25.400 --> 00:46:26.740
there, are able to.

00:46:26.740 --> 00:46:30.400
It's a matter of if they
have enough people.

00:46:30.400 --> 00:46:30.570
Yeah?

00:46:30.570 --> 00:46:32.305
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:46:32.305 --> 00:46:35.746
you said earlier, the
surrounding areas were very

00:46:35.746 --> 00:46:37.983
dependent on turtle
harvesting.

00:46:37.983 --> 00:46:41.200
Has that changed?

00:46:41.200 --> 00:46:43.620
DR. CALEB MCCLENNEN:
Historically, Belize before it

00:46:43.620 --> 00:46:47.430
was Belize, when it was British
Honduras, as a colony,

00:46:47.430 --> 00:46:50.200
the turtle fishery was the
dominant fishery for several

00:46:50.200 --> 00:46:50.880
hundred years.

00:46:50.880 --> 00:46:52.620
It was the most lucrative and
the biggest thing that was out

00:46:52.620 --> 00:46:54.700
there, which says something
about the relative size of the

00:46:54.700 --> 00:46:57.670
colony but also the abundance
of turtles at that time when

00:46:57.670 --> 00:46:59.670
you're talking several
orders of magnitude.

00:46:59.670 --> 00:47:03.090
Today, turtles are worth
a lot for eco-tourism.

00:47:03.090 --> 00:47:06.270
They're not worth anything in
terms of financial resources.

00:47:06.270 --> 00:47:08.610
In other countries like
Nicaragua, people are selling

00:47:08.610 --> 00:47:12.070
green turtles on the local
market, 100% for meat

00:47:12.070 --> 00:47:14.670
for $25, $35 each.

00:47:14.670 --> 00:47:15.540
So there's a small

00:47:15.540 --> 00:47:17.700
micro-economic dependence there.

00:47:17.700 --> 00:47:20.120
In reality, it's actually more
of a protein dependence,

00:47:20.120 --> 00:47:23.320
because 10,000 turtles is
quite a lot of meat.

00:47:23.320 --> 00:47:27.030
But as a driver of trade, CITES,
the regime I mentioned

00:47:27.030 --> 00:47:30.230
previously, has effectively
banned most turtle trade for

00:47:30.230 --> 00:47:32.260
the shell or for the meat.

00:47:32.260 --> 00:47:34.790
So now, if you looked
at analysis--

00:47:34.790 --> 00:47:36.110
I'm sure there are
some out there--

00:47:36.110 --> 00:47:38.640
the value of turtles is
tremendously larger in terms

00:47:38.640 --> 00:47:41.680
of just scuba diving and
people seeing them.

00:47:41.680 --> 00:47:43.550
But not anymore.

00:47:43.550 --> 00:47:45.460
Fisheries are still
quite valuable.

00:47:45.460 --> 00:47:49.077
And shark, as you mentioned,
shark fin is quite valuable in

00:47:49.077 --> 00:47:50.860
the places that don't
protect shark.

00:47:50.860 --> 00:47:54.860
There's a lot of money coming
in for the fin in Belize and

00:47:54.860 --> 00:47:57.480
everywhere in the world.

